                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/1035: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitehouse</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-12-29T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 29, 1930—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>80. Your 128, December 28, 8 p.m. Department concurs in your four recommendations
                    to General Orellana and it attaches imperative importance to the second point.
                    The Department believes that it would vitiate the new provisional Government
                    were any of the persons concerned with the military movement of December 16
                    carried over into it. If such further action seems necessary, you may inform
                    General Orellana of the attitude of the Government of the United States in that
                    respect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
